<article class="about">
  <h1>About MMIX</h1>

  <h2>What Is This?</h2>
  <p>
    This app has a specific purpose: to make it easier to get through
    <em>The Art of Computer Programming</em> (TAOCP) by Donald Knuth. There are two
    problems with the textbooks: they are very hard to read, and the existing tools for
    writing the code are GNU utilities and command-line builds that deter newcomers. I
    can't do jack about problem one (still working on that myself), but I can do
    something about problem two. The books are hard; the tooling shouldn't be.
  </p>

  <h2>What Is MMIX?</h2>
  <p>
    To demonstrate his algorithms, Knuth invented his own computer. MMIX is a
    "polyunsaturated" (imaginary) 64-bit RISC architecture that models the features
    common to real modern processors. (It replaced an older imaginary computer called
    MIX, which described big iron from the Apollo era.) The assembly language for this
    imaginary computer is MMIXAL &mdash; and that's what you can write and run here, in
    your browser. Under the hood, this simulator compiles Knuth's own C implementation
    to WebAssembly, so there's nothing to install.
  </p>

  <h2>Try It</h2>
  <p>Paste this into the editor and hit Run:</p>
  <pre><code>          LOC   #100
Main      GETA  $255,String
          TRAP  0,Fputs,StdOut
          TRAP  0,Halt,0
String    BYTE  "Greetings, Programmer!",#a,0</code></pre>
  <p>
    That prints "Greetings, Programmer!" to standard output and halts. That's it; you're
    writing MMIXAL.
  </p>

  <h2>Why Bother?</h2>
  <p>
    In print since 1968, TAOCP keeps finding new readers, decade after decade. It's a
    math-first, machine-level treatment of algorithms &mdash; the kind of fundamentals
    that don't expire when the next framework drops. Even the tools we're all talking
    about now are built on this stuff: in early 2026, Filip Stappers used an LLM to
    <a href="https://www-cs-faculty.stanford.edu/~knuth/papers/claude-cycles.pdf"
       target="_blank" rel="noopener">solve an open problem from a forthcoming TAOCP
    volume</a>, and Knuth wrote it up himself. You always need to know what the hell
    you're doing, whether you're writing the code or prompting the thing that writes the
    code. And honestly? It's fun.
  </p>

  <h2>Go To It</h2>
  <p>
    TAOCP is a classic doorstopper that invites the foolhardy programmer to join in the
    Quixotic pursuit of actually reading it. There's enough friction in the books
    themselves without throwing additional barriers in the way. If you want to charge at
    the windmill that is <em>The Art of Computer Programming</em>, this is your lance.
  </p>
  <p>
    If you want to see how this has been put together under the hood, the
    <a href="https://github.com/Wirt4/mmix-simulator" target="_blank"
       rel="noopener">source is on GitHub</a>.
  </p>
</article>
